newsitem.title: USA: Indications China a seller in U.S. soymeal market.
newsitem.headline: Indications China a seller in U.S. soymeal market.

text.p: There are indications China has been a seller of an unspecified quantity of soymeal in U.S. cash markets in the last several days, export sources said.
"They (China) have been noted as sellers," one Ohio River dealer said. "I don't know if they are cancelling business or selling back some previously taken on positions, but they are sellers."
Markets at the Chicago Board of Trade have been rife with rumors that China was reselling soymeal to capture a profit following recent rallies in soymeal futures, CBOT traders and cash sources said.
In similar activity, China last week was said to have resold 25,000 tonnes of Argentine soyoil to a commercial firm after soyoil futures rallied sharply, sources said.
Traders in Hong Kong said that soymeal arrivals to China from South America and India were heavy and values were falling as a result.
"It makes sense that China might wash out of some positions," one U.S. export source said.
"Meal prices have been coming down in China because they have enough oil and meal right now, and I don't see them as buyers until after the Chinese New Year on February 7," he said.
Some other export sources said that the U.S. soymeal market has been very quiet in the past several days and they saw no signs that China was a seller.
